The government wants to limit the torture of "witches", according to a brochure published in
Women considered as witches in Burkina Faso share certain characteristics.
They are usually elderly, unable to work, for example, for health reasons, are single and have no children.
Women who "return" witches are sent to an isolated area, so as not to harm the rest of the village.
"Men rarely suffer such a bell."
“Healthy young women are not isolated either, because they help in the work and have children,” explains a nun who, in the West African state capital, Burkina Faso is engaged in a special residence of more than a hundred women expelled from their communities.
The local government has decided to oppose this unusual "social measure".
He issued an information leaflet that should help to avoid witch-hunting.
However, this has a catch.
“More than 70% of adults in Burkina Faso can’t read,” warns Die Standard newspaper about the disadvantages of written sensitization.
Accusations of witchcraft are also common in other African countries.
In Ghana, neighbouring Burkina Faso, 72-year-old Ammy Hemmah died last week when three women and two men tortured her, covered her with gasoline and burned her.
The news appeared on the BBC.
The authors claim that it was due to an unfortunate set of circumstances.
According to her version, the woman was burned in the oil used for ritual anointings.
It was set on fire when the group wanted to "expel the evil spirits" from the woman.
The isolation of "witches" is supported by people of all educational levels.
The Der Standard newspaper quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso: “Human soul eaters have always posed a danger,” he said.
While in Burkina Faso the government is trying to appease the witch-hunt, in The Gambia last year the president still participated in it.
“Gambian President Jammeh, after the death of his aunt, launched a large-scale hunt for witches who had allegedly been linked to his death and had attempted to kill the president himself through black magic.”
“To help him, he brought shamans from nearby Guinea who, protected by police, military and the president’s personal escort, forcibly took randomly chosen men and women from Gambian peoples to the president’s property in Kanilai,” Amnesty International said in its report.
At the farm, the arrested people had to drink a potion of herbs with hallucinogenic effects that, in addition, caused them intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of the arrested did not survive the stay at the farm.
After international pressure, they finally released about a thousand detainees.
Bakala tenant: heats up with coal stoves and signs higher rent
The man, elderly and reclusive, crossed the doors of the customer service center of the company RPG Byty of the "coal magnate" Zde<0xC5><0x88>ek Bakala, the largest private owner of flats for rent in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm he was carrying documents with the new three-story rental contracts: his, that of his daughter and that of his son, who is serving sentence.
All three of them have just been caught up in the liberalization of rents.
Instead of 3,500 Czech crowns per month, the child will pay from next year 4,100 crowns for a two-room apartment with separate second-class kitchen.
"In addition, it does not have hot water and the heating is based on a solid fuel boiler," the man shows with his finger in his son's new contract, on whose signature he has full powers.
"But I signed it," he explains half angry, half resigned.
The civil association BytyOKD.cz, which described the new rental conditions as "incorrect and indecent", recommends that tenants do not sign the new contracts and wait until December 7, when it will publish a guide informing on how to proceed in these cases.
But, before this, man only makes a breath.
"Everyone says one thing," he says with a bad face.
Ostrava is becoming a major testing laboratory for liberalization.
After the New Year it will happen with the vast majority of the flats that, in the Czech Republic, were so far under a regulated rent.
Therefore, Aktu<0xC3><0xA1>ln<0xC4><0x9B>.cz decided to visit the "laboratory" in person.
The RPG mining waiting room is one of four in Ostrava and, on Tuesday at nine, it was already full.
Right next to the doors are the security guards and next to them a machine to pick up number.
"Rent 2011", can be read on a bright button of your touch screen.
When you press it, a piece of paper with a number comes out of the machine.
Almost no time to read "157" and already the number appears on the large screen located at the top of the room.
In a second, you're in line.
Soon after, an elderly couple arrives to ask, but the crowd in the room is not here for the new rentals.
Most people come to solve common problems, as in the past: requests for arrangements, insurance issues and similar matters.
The letters with the new rental contracts will arrive in Ostrava to the mailboxes of the tenants of most of the 44,000 floors belonging to RPG around mid-November.
RPG Byty proposes in the cards an increase in the rent of between 15 and 38%.
On November 18, a special window opens in the customer service center for new rentals.
“It’s been running for a week, so it’s starting,” the workers who are in it when the client presents themselves as a journalist answer, after briefly doubting.
The liberalization and former Bakala mining floors are the most sensitive issues in the area.
Before the elections, they were already treated high and clear by the vice-president of the Parliament, originally from Ostrava, Lubom<0xC3><0xAD>r Zaor<0xC3><0xA1>lek, of the <0xC4><0x8C>SSD, and now they appear continuously in the newspapers of the area.
“Twenty years later, I want a new floor.”
“I didn’t even change the damn bathroom dish,” the man mentioned in the introduction exhales.
According to the workers, for the moment they come more than anything retired to check if they receive a discount on the rent if they sign on time, as promised by the special offer of RPG.
The remaining tenants who sign the new contract before December 15 will also receive half of the discount on the February rent.
However, the window of the mining "liberalization" certainly does not manage to dispel the avalanche of doubts.
“Of the 360 customers who were here yesterday, only about forty or fifty people asked about the rental in 2011,” the window employee said.
Meanwhile, RPG proposes to hold individual meetings on contracts on the web and on its boards when necessary.
If the two parties do not reach an agreement on the lease, an independent judge will have to resolve the matter.
“This is not a threat, but information about the only possible way to proceed and fully comply with the law,” the company said in a statement.
“No one is going to be judged here,” says one of the employees of RPG Byty and a man who is on the street in front of the customer service center gives him, at least in part, the reason.
“I get a pension of 13,000 and I have 5,000 left for food; I have no means to go to court,” he says.
But, immediately, the employee sows the doubt.
"We'll see."
"Mr. Zaor<0xC3><0xA1>lek warns them in the media not to sign, so maybe people will wait," he said.
Rent regulation will cease to exist in most of the Czech Republic in early 2011 and, according to RPG Byty, its increase is an economic necessity.
“The current rents still don’t even cover the amounts necessary for the maintenance of the community fund,” recalls Pavel Klime<0xC5><0xA1>, director of the residential portfolio of the company RPG Byty, who adds that the careless state of the community fund that annoys tenants is, for owners, the main reason for increasing rent.
While during the five years between 2005 and 2010 RPG was able to invest with the rents in apartments four billion, in the four years that will go from 2011 to 2014 the figure will increase to 5.2 billion.
The large screen hanging from the ceiling, in front of the waiting room seats, now repeats some data that stands out in red.
"The increase in rental in 2011 by 15% and less applies to 31,200 apartments, i.e. more than 90% of RPG properties."
“In addition, it will always be a maximum of 7.50 Czech crowns per square meter per month,” the screen reads.
Only increased by 38% the rental of 400 floors of the RPG portfolio.
“In such cases, it’s an increase from extremely low amounts, of 19.66 crowns per square meter,” says RPG.
In 2,600 flats, the rent will remain unchanged next year.
RPG Byty promises that liberalization will not hit rents at once, but will scale up between four and eight years.
In addition, he adds the following commitment: the company will invest all the money from the rise of the rent (see the graph) again on the floors, mainly in heating savings: new windows and heating.
Priority will be given to the people who sign the rental rise agreement.
Architects have understood that offices also need daycare
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
No one would say that it also hides inside a small nursery with everything similar to such facilities: colorful walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outdoor terrace.
Since October of last year, the children of Arch.Design employees can go to it.
The architectural project company Arch.Design, whose studio came out of numerous well-known buildings in Brno, thought from the first sketches of the Avriopoint building to include a space for its mini-kindergarten.
The company employs around 90 people, mainly at the age of the baby boom and wanted to allow architects and designers to return to work soon after motherhood.
Along with the possibility of enjoying a reduced schedule, the nursery is one of the benefits offered by Arch.Design to its workers within the framework of its social program.
Builders and architects thus have the possibility to combine a demanding profession with childcare.
The mini-kindergarten was an idea of Arch.Designu’s own employees and, with the support of the management, they managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company’s mini-kindergarten is financed through the European Social Fund under the Operational Programme for Human Resources and Employment, as well as the state budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the funding granted (a grant of more than 2.8 million Czech crowns) they were able to buy the equipment and, after two years, hire qualified personnel and services.
When funding runs out (two years), Arch.Design has an obligation to keep the mini-kindergarten running with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and the company Economy Rating contributed to the submission of the application for funding.
The care of the children is in the hands of qualified staff; in addition, a nurse and a teacher from the Ministry of Education are present all day for their care. The nursery currently welcomes children without age limit, although most of them are less than three years old.
Since it is a "mini-kindergarten", it can only accommodate a maximum of five children simultaneously, although with shifts they come more during the day.
The operation of the nursery is flexible to adapt to the needs of parents and children of all workers have the same right to use the nursery, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although it is an individual education and care, the contents of the mini-kindergarten program are comparable to the regular preschool curriculum.
In it, children not only play, but also receive quality education: from basic learning to school preparation, they teach up to English.
The class not only has toys and board games, but also a computer for children.
The presence of young children in the company itself create a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can go to see their children at any time and avoid the stress of late picking up school children when they are away from their workplace.
Thus, parents are more productive while working.
It is not surprising that this naturally generates a relationship of loyalty between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design ranks among the firms that offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, in short, this program strengthened staff marketing.
The House of Bones continues to fascinate after 100 years.
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs resemble the column of a dinosaur, and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, in Barcelona, by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
Due to its shape similar to a skeleton, the locals nicknamed it "the house of bones".
Its organic forms, its striking colors, the innovative use of stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade reminiscent of the scales and the ubiquitous lines gently curved, all this is typical of the secession of Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
The cover of the house plays with dreamy lines, delicate colors and textures taken from nature and fauna.
Paying more attention, one observes a certain geometry, rhythm and a carefully thought-out order.
At night, the entire facade of the house looks even more impressive, since it is illuminated in such a way that the brightness of the colors is improved.
Serpentea and the twisting of the forms continues to surprise us also inside.
The corrugated wood copies the frames of the windows, the railings, the ornaments of the doors, the mirrors and the signs.
Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, located in the Eixample district at number 43 of the lively shopping street of Passeig de Gr<0xC3><0xA0>cia, emerged from the refurbishment of an 1877 house by the architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, initially insisted on demolishing the previous building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s idea of a novel and cheaper reconstruction.
However, Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, consisting of several apartments, was not designed by Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> alone.
The architect Josep Mar<0xC3><0xAD>a Jujol collaborated in the design.
In fact, in their plans of the project emerged ornaments for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the mosaics used on the facade.
Other creators and artists also work on the fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade.
The collaboration in the proposals of Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3> was the beginning of Jujol’s successful collaboration with Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
Jujol participated in the construction of Casa Mila and Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s G<0xC3><0xBC>ell Park, where other pieces of it are located.
Due to its organic form, the locals soon after its completion nicknamed it "the house of bones".
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening the windows began to call it "the house of yawns".
It is also said that, at the top of the construction, the sword of San Jorge, patron of Catalonia, appears.
Other sculptural elements of the construction hide religious motifs.
Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> designed in the house a unique system for the central heating season with ventilation vents and typical fireplaces.
It may be strange your inclination of forty-five degrees.
During the construction, Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> did not respect the construction rules of the moment at all and was not influenced by them.
Even so, the construction obtained the corresponding permission from the beginning, although obviously in it the data indicated on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, at its completion, the town hall was so shocked with the result that it asked for correction.
He was annoyed, for example, that the construction included columns even up to the public sidewalk.
Arrangements were never made, quite the contrary: just fifteen days after the request of the town hall, Josep Batll<0xC3><0xB3> requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
On the lower floors the owner himself was installed.
In the gallery on the second floor was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented out to a jewelry store.
The six-story house is completely traversed by a staircase leading up to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted in breaking all the angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> also worked with the modern concept of the connection of space.
The common part can be fully connected by opening the doors of the rooms and a larger group can communicate in this way without problems, without giving up the privacy necessary for more intimate conversations.
The house, with the reconstruction of Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>, not only got a new facade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> plays with light, white and blue tiles that cover the inner courtyard and skylights.
The play with the two colors provides maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was based simply on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which on the contrary absorb sunlight.
Anyone can visit Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and most reloaded apartment of those accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that it is a very beneficial business and extended the visits to the common area and the attic, including the roof terrace.
The price of the entrance to the monument is not insignificant, it reaches 16.50 euros, although students, retirees and holders of tourist cards get a 20% discount.
The amount considerably exceeds the price of the entrance of other Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> buildings in the city.
If you want to enjoy the real atmosphere of the bed with its lizard towers, you should quickly make friends with a resident of the neighboring houses and visit him at home.
How to choose the mattress and the somier: women and men look for different things
Nothing of a pompous frame for the bed; what really confers its quality to a good bed is the surface to lie down, that is, the mattress and the sommer.
First of all, they must be perfectly complemented in order to adapt to specific users.
During the election, numerous elements come into play, including the weight, height, health status and gender of the owner.
Also important is the type of interior in which the mattress and sommer are located.
A typical example?
For example, in a weekend cabin that does not usually have heating, latex mattresses should not be used because they "warm up" more slowly.
In addition, they usually weigh considerably more than the usual polyurethane mattresses.
Therefore, it is necessary to turn them more often.
If the channels in the center are not properly ventilated and, above, they are on a firm base, they keep the moisture inside.
When choosing a bed, habits also influence.
Those who have spent a lot of time abroad often use a very high mattress with a soft layer and will have trouble feeling good on a lower and harder surface.
“Almost every hockey player who came back from the NHL complained that they didn’t sleep as well here.”
"For their crushed shoulders, heels and hips they needed mattresses with a soft layer of viscoelastic."
"These types of mattresses are also recommended for people with diabetes who have problems with the nervous system, so they receive poorly information from joints and skin," explains Sylva Hadamczikov<0xC3><0xA1>, who specializes in upholstered furniture.
Many hockey players, like other customers, have been preferring viscoelastic mattresses for some time.
"Today there is no problem, because they have these suitable Tempur and the Italian Magniflex, but also the Czech brand Tropico."
You no longer have to be an NHL player to appreciate the viscoelastic.
This "miracle" works in a very simple way.
It optimizes its stiffness and shape depending on the absorbed heat or adapts to your body heat.
Nothing exerts pressure; during the night, it will not spin like after a hard match.
He just sleeps better.
Viscoelastic also works as a protection against sores.
When choosing the size of the mattress, add to its height the length of your feet, that is, between 21 and 34 cm.
A man or woman with a height of about 180 cm will need a bed of between 210 and 220 cm.
The minimum width for a person should be, in a double room, 90 cm, in total 180 cm.
In the case of single rooms, for example singles, a minimum of 120 to 140 cm is recommended.
So that a possible visit is also comfortable.
"If not, you can apply a simple rule to calculate the width: when lying face up, you should have your hands comfortably shrunk to the elbows," advises the engineer Helena Prokopov<0xC3><0xA1>, an expert at Cechu <0xC4><0x8D>aloun<0xC3><0xAD>k<0xC5><0xAF> a dekoratér<0xC5><0xAF>, who has been dealing with the problem of healthy sleep and the special issue of school mobility for many years.
In double rooms, each one needs its own somier and mattress, so during the purchase you have to pay attention to combine the height of the mattresses.
Otherwise, it will be necessary to mount the bed bases at different heights, which is not always possible in all beds.
Foam mattresses should have a minimum height of 14 cm, models with inner springs a minimum of 15 cm, of which at least three centimeters are for the layer that adapts to the shapes and softness.
“By touching it with your hand or by sleeping on the mattress, you should definitely not notice the docks,” warns Helena Prokopov<0xC3><0xA1>.
Each mattress requires a certain type of mattress.
The fully padded bedrooms, in which the mattress and base are like Siamese, make no sense in the bedroom.
Mattresses breathe poorly and you can not wash their cover, which today is often done.
And, since we sweat between 0.2 and 0.75 l of sweat every night, it is clear that after about five or seven years the mattress will begin to remind us of a large (and congested) screen.
For this reason, specialists reject slogans that speak of a mattress life of up to 25 years or even a lifetime guarantee.
However, everything has a but.
Therefore, sellers give a tip: in mattresses with a width of 120 or 140 cm, take care of cleaning and washing the cover carefully, but better add a mattress protector that can be easily removed and washed.
Although currently manufactured zippered mattress covers throughout its perimeter, so when opening them they remain in two parts (something very important for washing and the size of the washing machine!), their manipulation in the larger models (and by a single person) when lifting the mattress can seem like a fight between a fly weight and a heavy weight.
In bed, instead of a soother, do you have a firm board?
Never! Never!
At least for the beds designed for overnight visits.
However, it should make (if you don’t already have them) ventilation holes in the table and should be used with a mattress with springs inside and a minimum height of 15 cm with springs in bags (such as the German Taschenfederkern) and a soft layer.
Polyurethane mattresses should not be used on such bases.
For non-jointable sheet bottoms and containing between 14 and 18 sheets, latex mattresses or sandwich mattresses (e.g., a combination of latex and coconut fiber) may be used, although it is always better to have a bottom with a greater number of sheets, 28 or more, in which the regular sheets of the lumbar region are reinforced and can be stiffened.
Jointed sheet underlays should not be used with a spring mattress, as it does not react to reclining.
In addition to adjusting the rigidity of the sheets, shoulder protection can also be used.
It is a special fixation of the sheets that allows you to press or even tilt the sheets so that they "round" perfectly to the shoulders during sleep.
For men who have very wide shoulders, this is very important.
They are even remembered by mattress manufacturers who, in the "masculine", began to use a softer area precisely around the shoulders.
They also remember women, for whom they put a softer area around the hips.
For the most demanding customers, there are soles with cross structure or boards with the so-called multi-torsion damping.
The pressure is distributed between different points and the voltage is lowered.
It should also be borne in mind that, even if you use the right mattress and soother, if you use a bad pillow (large and "mullida"), most of the advantages will disappear.
The basic rule is simple: the pillow should hold the head and the corners can only reach the shoulders, so that the muscles of the same can be relaxed.
The recommended suitable size is 50 x 60 cm, something normal for example in Scandinavia.
When lying on the side, the pillow should be at the same level (when combined with the somier with shoulder reinforcement or the softer area of the mattress) as the height of the shoulders.
Modern mattresses have something to do with, it seems, the original mattresses filled with straw.
Manufacturers continue to use, more and more often, natural materials or at least mixtures.
In fact, biological mattresses are fashionable.
Petroleum-based raw materials, with which polyurethane foam is made, are filled with natural oils, for example castor or soybean.
In fact, virtually all known manufacturers use soy.
“Organic, in the case of mattresses, means that the center is made only of materials of natural origin,” explains Petr Va<0xC5><0xA1><0xC3><0xAD><0xC4><0x8D>ek from Tropico Plus.
Also, natural substances are used during the manufacture of the mattress cover, one of the first aloe vera.
But you can also opt for microcapsules, which release a fresh scent to forest or lavender.
There are also differences for men and women.
While men "refresh" with vegetable extracts of breeze, so that the mattress cover absorbs the heat and refreshes the body, women prefer to "warm up" the cover.
Red pepper extract improves blood circulation, so that women feel more warmth.
Favorites currently?
The mattresses made of cold foam, which are more porous, with an adapted cell structure, which makes them more permeable than those of normal polyurethane and offer more permeability.
The combination of various rigidities of cold foam and viscoelastic make it possible to manufacture mattresses from various areas that know perfectly where the head, shoulders and heels go.
A good quality mattress will cost you seven thousand crowns up.
Those who perform a therapeutic function usually have a lower VAT, since they are considered as health means.
The first to gain this advantage in the Czech Republic was Gumotex.
It is difficult to save on mattresses and bedspreads.
Sometimes you can approve offers from manufacturers or sellers, who sometimes offer two mattresses for the price of one.
For example, the Magniflex brand offers Duofreeze mattresses with a Memory foam attached to the case for 11,990 crowns.
The second is obtained free of charge.
The era of viscoelastic with an open cell structure and high density began with Tempur's "cosmic" material.
It initially emerged as material for NASA, because during takeoff astronauts were subjected to a huge overload.
Tempur softens with heat and hardens with cold.
Therefore, the human body, warm, exerts a perfect effect and optimally adapts its pressure.
Therefore, it is ideal to prevent sores from occurring, but also to improve comfort during sleep.
