According to Pilin de Macro Weil, for this reason, tests are currently being carried out with devices that look like a digital clock.
"In addition, they will have the added advantage that a potential attacker may not identify the device."
“Or that I identify it after a certain time, which can make the police gain time,” he adds.
Although tracking devices are worn on the wrist or hanging, they will continue to use the same technology used for vehicle tracking.
It is a position check with a GPS system (which is used in the usual navigation in the car) combined with the function of a mobile phone that communicates the current position.
