Czech young people get drunk with Fernet and rum. The beer is no longer so, because it affects slowly
Fernet, rum, vodka and even good whiskeys stolen from his parents.
Those are the drinks that cause young drinkers under the age of fifteen to end up in medical care.
Children who end up lying in hospital continuously to overcome the hangover are no longer an exception.
This is derived from the experience of doctors encountering such cases in hospital pediatric admissions.
"Drinking beer or wine is no longer fashionable, because it takes a long time to get them drunk."
“Now fashion is strong alcoholic beverages,” says Lud<0xC4><0x9B>k Pelik<0xC3><0xA1>n, head of pediatrics at the Ho<0xC5><0x99>ovice Hospital in central Bohemia.
"When they manage to get a bottle from their father from the pantry, it may be whiskey, but it's usually Fernet and vodka."
“Vodka has the advantage of being lightened with juice and not smelling so much,” he explains.
This is also confirmed by the spokesperson of the Motol University Hospital, Eva Jurinov<0xC3><0xA1>.
"Normally, it's Fernet or rum."
"These are modern alcoholic beverages, particularly among schoolchildren."
"In some cases, they use brandy that they took at home," Jurinov<0xC3><0xA1> adds.
According to Chief Pelik<0xC3><0xA1>n, it is thirteen and fourteen-year-old drinkers who usually appear in hospitals.
Before Ho<0xC5><0x99>ovice, where he has been working since this year, he worked for a decade in pediatrics at Motol, where ambulances took young people from nearby areas.
"A girl had to come in maybe four times."
“It started at the age of twelve, when she was brought in with 3.5 alcohol in her blood, plus a mixture with ecstasy,” the department’s doctor said in a statement.
"He was at Hole<0xC5><0xA1>ovice fair at a dance party."
“The interesting thing is that his mother wasn’t even surprised that his daughter disappeared for 48 hours,” he said.
It is precisely the lack of interest from parents or even their clear tolerance towards drinking on the part of their children that is considered the main cause of the increase in alcohol consumption among young people.
Experts point out that, in the case of children, dependence cannot be properly spoken of.
“An alcoholic is a person who has been chronically dependent on alcohol for several years, with all the phenomena associated with it, which does not occur in children.”
“In those who drink alcohol repeatedly, it is rather due to a systematically failed social or family environment,” Pelik<0xC3><0xA1>n explains.
According to spokeswoman Jurinov<0xC3><0xA1>, this year in the pediatric clinic of Motol were hospitalized until mid-November forty drunk children.
However, the statistics only show those who come with a serious poisoning and must stay in the hospital.
Young drinkers who, after medical recognition, go home with their parents or with the police, do not count.
In addition to the cases in which children simply gather after school and drink aguardiente, for Pelikan there are three seasonal ups and downs that should be mentioned: the day of witches, the end of the year and the end of the school year.
"In such a circumstance, they drink for the bad notes or, on the contrary, celebrate the beginning of the holiday."
"On the day of the witches I have come to see in admissions up to seven drunk children at a time," adds Pelikan.
Drinkers who spend the night in detox under the supervision of doctors, paradoxically, have the advantage that the next day they do not suffer a terrible hangover at home.
Morning headache, caused by dehydration and lack of glucose, is prevented by the injection of a serum with glucose and with the nutrients that the body lacks.
"They take it much better, because after a hectic night, they get up well and it hurts them nothing."
“They are only confused about where they are,” Pelik<0xC3><0xA1>n says, adding that patients often lose their good mood at least when they see the expenses they have generated.
The transfer by ambulance and hospitalization in a room for serious patients costs about ten thousand crowns.
“I have often used the cost as a means of educating them, when on the visit I tell them directly to the children how much their drunkenness has cost and that they would have to spend all summer in a youth job so that you earn enough to pay that night,” Pelikan adds.
