Can civility build a bridge to unite the divisions?
After a remarkable campaign for invective and negativity, this week has triggered a bit of civility in Washington.
Is it a omen of genuine bipartisan cooperation in the future or an illusory moment before a quick return to partisan combat in the capital?
Tuesday’s meeting between President Obama and Congressional leaders produced no progress on the major issues to be addressed during the outgoing session.
But as everyone says, it was at least a polite discussion about the differences between the two parties, as well as a recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than being another empty episode to gain partisan points.
Wednesday’s public meeting of the president’s deficit commission was equally civilised, despite the political differences that remain between members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months generated mutual respect that transcends the ideological gap that still separates members.
That is hardly enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Now both sides are in a testing period, probing each other to identify signs of co-operativeism and commitment, as they try to assess the limits of public opinion and voters’ patience for a renewed partisan war.
This is the reason why the Tuesday meeting and subsequent evaluations of the same by the participants were made with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too great and are very deeply rooted to suggest any rapid climate change that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it’s taxes, expenses, health care or social assistance, the two sides are at opposite poles.
Anyway, the November election has softened the mood in Washington, at least in the short term.
“There’s no doubt that things have changed with regard to the way things are said,” said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now at the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
“They are inevitable after the election.
The elections arouse partisan passions, which then go extinct.
That's good."
On some issues, particularly those on the agenda of the outgoing session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush’s tax cuts are due at the end of the year, and no one is in favor of this.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve some or all of the reductions, either permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, there is likely to be a commitment to expand unemployment benefits, probably because Republicans can’t make you believe they’re in favor of tax cuts for the rich, denying the unemployment benefit for the unemployed workers.
After Tuesday’s meeting at the White House, there is increased optimism about a possible deal on these issues during the outgoing session, along with the ratification of the new START (Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty) nuclear disarmament pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on pressing issues of the outgoing session will not necessarily lead to continued bipartisanship when the new 112th Congress meets in January.
He said, on the contrary, that it is very likely and even inevitable that a period of disagreement will begin.
“After the things that need to be done are carried out, in the short term psychology will turn the situation into a confrontational one,” he said.
Wehner also expressed skepticism (which is widely shared) about the fact that civility can lead to true cooperation.
“I see most of what will happen between now and 2012 as an essay for the 2012 main event,” he said.
The reasons have a lot to do with the constitution of the new Republican majority in the House and the Tea Party voters, who contributed decisively to its creation.
As much as Republican leaders are aware of the dangers of exaggerating their position, they know they must try to live up to their promises to cut state spending and overturn the new health law.
Those lines of support are already clearly seen in the initial reactions to the deficit commission’s recommendations, which include reforming the tax code and increasing some taxes and retirement age, and cutting spending.
Co-chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken care of one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and, in their own assessment, have forcibly introduced the issue of the deficit on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member committee to publish their plan as an official recommendation, and have been struggling to get close to that figure.
The greatest resistance is among the elected officials on the panel, suggesting that in tax matters there is, at least currently, little basis or desire for compromise.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between the Republicans in the White House and those in Congress.
The first will happen next year in the form of partisan clashes, when Republicans challenge Obama on the budget, taxes and medical care, followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would cause the change?
Public opinion.
There is considerable evidence that, despite the partisanship of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If the confrontation leads to a dead end, as happened in 1995, then both parties will watch closely the reaction of the people.
Anyone who thinks they’re losing is likely to change course and seek engagement.
However, this can be an optimistic view.
The partisanship and polarization are currently greater than they were in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a larger ideological gap between Obama and Republicans in Congress than there was between President Bill Clinton and Republicans at the time.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as the mere prelude to a more momentous election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civilization shown this week can be welcomed by many Americans.
But this will require much more effort on the part of both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
A leaked U.S. document portrays Moscow as the paradise of corruption
Control of the city is in the hands of a “cleptocracy,” and it leaves a portion of the bribes and protection money it collects directly to the Kremlin, the U.S. Embassy in Russia reported in February.
It was reported that both the police and the Federal Security Service run huge blackmail systems, which helps explain the high cost of living in Moscow.
They raise money not only from legitimate businesses, but also from organized criminal groups.
Each stratum of bureaucracy, what Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has called “vertical authority,” takes its share as money climbs the scale.
The note, which was sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was posted by WikiLeaks on its website on Wednesday.
The note is based on sources whose names have been censored.
It was written while Yuri Luzhkov was still mayor of Moscow, and he blames it for much of the corruption.
President Dmitry Medvedev fired him in October, but there has been little evidence of a cleanup since then.
Luzhkov and his wife, Yelena Baturina, who owns a major construction company, have consistently denied corruption allegations over the years, and he has won several libel lawsuits over such allegations.
In September, when asked on a Russian television channel about a documentary that suggested it was corrupt, he stated: “It’s crazy, it’s crazy, it’s annoying.”
According to polls, Russians overwhelmingly believe their society is corrupt.
But it is unusual to find the details explained in detail, as they were in the embassy report, and it is unheard of for diplomats from a foreign country to do so.
"The direct links of the Moscow city government to crime have led some to call it 'disfunctional', and to claim that the government functions more as a kleptocracy than as a government," it said.
“Criminal elements enjoy a ‘krysha’ (a term of the criminal and mafia world that literally means ‘roof’ or protection) that bypasses the police, the Federal Security Service (SFS), the Ministry of Internal Affairs (MVD), and the prosecutor’s office, as well as all sectors of the Moscow city government’s bureaucracy.
"Analysts identify a three-tiered structure in Moscow's criminal world."
"Luzhkov is at the top."
"The SFS, the MVD and the militia are on the second level."
“Finally, common criminals and corrupt inspectors are at the lowest level.”
“This is an ineffective system in which criminal groups fill a void in some areas because the city does not provide some services.”
The report states that the SFS collects money from larger companies, and that the police target small businesses.
One source, the report said, “explained that Moscow’s commercial owners understand that it is best to get protection from MVD and SFS (rather than organized crime groups) as they not only have more weapons, resources and power than criminal groups, but are also protected by law.”
“For this reason, protection against criminal gangs is no longer a priority.”
The note notes that while the collection of money is complete, protection may be irregular; even those who pay are subject to arrest.
Those who don’t pay quickly find their businesses closed under one pretext or another.
Medvedev has spoken several times about the fight against corruption, but he has confessed that he has made little progress.
The embassy note reports about men taking suitcases, probably full of cash, inside the Kremlin itself.
"In his fight against corruption, Medvedev has to trust the bureaucrats," Georgy Satarov, director of the Indem expert group in Moscow, said in a recent interview.
"But he's a part of this bureaucracy."
"He does not belong to a political class, because there is no longer a political class in Russia."
Without politics, without an opposition, without a separation of powers, he said, corruption is inevitable.
At the national level, Indem estimates that corruption costs Russia more than $300 billion a year.
In a recent survey on global perceptions of corruption conducted by the non-governmental organization Transparency International, the country was ranked 154th (countries are ranked from least to most corrupt).
The revelation of the U.S. Embassy note, which did not happen until late at night Moscow time, will surely cause disgust within the Russian government, and even though Luzhkov may be blamed for Moscow’s weaknesses, it could be an opportunity for the Kremlin to argue that it is solving the problem.
Interviewed for CNN by Larry King, Putin suggested that the WikiLeaks documents could be lies and reacted furiously to a revelation that U.S. diplomats called him Batman and Medvedev Robin.
“The truth of the matter is that this is related to our interaction, which is an important factor of domestic policies in this country,” he said.
“But to be honest with you, we don’t suspect that this would have been done with such arrogance, with such pressure, and, you know, that it would have been done in such an immoral way.”
