Since Red Bull broke into the world of Formula One in 2004, its history in this select universe of speed has been marked by surprise and success.
At first no one took into account the options of a newly arrived team and, despite the upward trajectory of the last seasons, last November, in the final straight of the championship everyone bet on the victory of Ferrari Fernando Alonso.
Without depreciating the skill as a driver of the final champion, the German Sebastian Vettel, nor the ability of the Renault engine that propels his car, in the world of Formula 1 has become a legend the "secret weapon" that the multinational Siemens has put in the hands of Red Bull to turn it into a winning team.
It is actually a powerful process simulation software that the German put on the market in 2007 for purposes far away from high automotive competition.
Called PLM, this powerful computing instrument has been used to design assembly lines from manufacturing factories around the world, power plants, high-precision instruments.
The goal is to reproduce, faithfully simulate the product or process before building it in a real way, thus avoiding avoidable failures and costs.
PLM has facilitated the development of Canon’s cameras, Sukhoi’s planes or Nissan’s most celebrated utility cars.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of Siemens’ industrial division, explains that the use of this computing instrument in his Formula 1 factory has allowed Red Bull to design and implement “in a few hours, almost in real time”, the modifications, changes and improvements that are detected during races and in trials.
Russwurm explains that the teams in 1992 had an average of 10 technicians on their team who were able to introduce a maximum of three or four improvements to the vehicles during each season.
The Red Bull team today employs 180 highly qualified young professionals who, equipped with powerful computer equipment, analyze and project all sorts of modifications to the bolides.
The CEO of Siemens explained that the PLM software is able to analyze and improve all the elements of the Red Bull bolides with the exception of the engine, which is the entire responsibility of Renault.
The materials, fuel, aerodynamics and safety elements are modified.
The changes can be brought from simulator virtual reality to reality in less than 24 hours, thanks to advanced laser production systems and high-tech autoclaves.
As the only limitation of this insanity of technological improvement is the $40 million figure that each Formula 1 team can spend at most in each season to facilitate competition.
Red Bull has set up the high-tech factory to design and produce their bolides in a town about 50 kilometres from London.
These are two buildings where visits are restricted, especially for journalists.
Everything that happens there is considered “high secret.”
The roster for this task amounts to 580 people, including its two drivers, champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
Red Bull’s Formula 1 hero is, without a doubt, the recent champion Sebastian Vetell.
Among the immense technological resources that the brand of energy drinks has put at the service of its participation in the circuits, there are other protagonists whose competition is priceless and their notoriety null.
Factory chief technology officer Steve Nevey says five years ago it could be said that R&D advances in carts accounted for 50% of victories and drivers were responsible for the rest.
Today these percentages have varied and the technology adds up to 85% of the success, while the drivers contribute 15% of the added value.
Nevey acknowledges that the Vettels or Webbers will never be replaced by computer science as "they are unpredictable gladiators."
HP to set up its own 20 stores with local distributors in two years
