Shoemaker and the German Red Line
Berlin has chosen to remain in the euro, but has set the conditions for the whole Union.
Tensions in the markets have led to a double government response.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodr<0xC3><0xAD>guez Zapatero has advanced new adjustment measures, from tax reductions to SMEs, regulation of private placement or suppression agencies of the 426 euros of aid to unemployed, to the privatization of 49% of AENA, the management of the airports of Barajas and El Prat and 30% of the State Lottery.
On the other hand, Vice-President Elena Salgado, with the support of former President Felipe Gonz<0xC3><0xA1>lez, has joined the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel for her responsibility in unleashing the current crisis.
How should these movements be interpreted?
Go ahead, Merkel’s position is not a mistake in her communication policy.
On the contrary, it is another turning point in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
And there Germany has a radically new vision of what its future must be, clashing with that of maintaining the old traditions of much of its partners.
In the face of European resistance, Germany is beginning to speculate on the three possible solutions to the crisis.
The first, a strong euro, made up of itself, Austria and the Netherlands, among other countries, while the south would leave the monetary zone.
The second, the recovery of the framework, although now it seems science fiction, with a very favorable current of opinion, close to 50% of the population.
The third, a redesign of the euro, in line with the German proposals for greater macroeconomic control, budgetary rigour, fines to transgressor countries, possible suspensions of payments of some of them and extension to the private sector of the costs of potential adjustments.
The German position is clear and has been defined for a long time, so now there are no excuses.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission stimulated deficits, the German government pulled out of the sleeve a constitutional reform to prevent them from 2016.
This was the first sign of divergence between what Germany believed should be done (plans of fiscal rigour and stability in public finances), and what its European partners, including France, were practicing.
The second on the front was given by the Central European country when Merkel painfully extended the decision to save Greece.
It was already the subject of fierce criticism at the time, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and the public opinion and the published opinion were very much against the rescue of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel again emerges with a clear position, demanding the reform of the Union treaties, to make it possible to save a country and, at the same time, force private lenders to run with part of the cost.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, as it has precipitated the Irish crisis and everything else.
But his proposal, although somewhat sweetened, has been approved and, in the coming months, we should be attending the process of reforming the Union to enable those measures from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
And he is telling us all that, even if we now have to take measures with which he may not agree very much, from that date the old functioning of the euro will have ended.
2013 will mean the birth of a new monetary area, in which the offending countries will be severely penalized, may be forced to declare themselves in default of payments and, in that case, the private sector will also run with part of the cost.
Germany is pointing out to us that we must follow a severe growth path with high savings and investment rates, moderation in consumption, improvements in productivity and competitiveness and positive external balances.
Another alternative based on debt and construction, with huge holes in the balance of payments, such as the one that has presided over Spanish growth in the boom years, simply will not tolerate it.
The invitation is clear.
And we'd be wrong not to understand it.
It’s not just about bringing the public deficit back to 3% in 2013.
What they demand of us is much harder.
And the worst thing we could do in these circumstances is deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will give way to greater calm.
And let us take advantage of the window of opportunity they have given us, until the spring of 2013.
It seems that President Zapatero has understood this as well and his double manifesto (the reforms promised after last Saturday’s meeting with big companies and yesterday’s announcement of new measures) suggests that, despite criticism of Merkel, the thesis that we must put order at home has opened up.
But the red line that Germany has drawn is there, and it doesn’t look like they’re going to move it.
And, among the possibilities that are contemplated, that of leaving a monetary zone too crowded with unserious countries, can not be excluded.
Then Germany will always be able to tell us that she had already warned us.
Sport and Law Fraud
Bullies such as Alonso and Ramos before Ajax show ingenuity but not willingness to escape a penalty.
The expulsion allegedly ordered by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the match played on November 23 against Ajax in the Champions League has caused ink rivers to be written about whether such behavior is or is not anti-sports and whether, eventually, both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, in the absence of a few minutes to finish the game (which his team had already clearly won), the two players deliberately lost time in taking fouls to cause the referee to show them the second yellow card.
That way, and since Real Madrid will end up as the leader of their group, both players will comply with the regulatory sanction the next match of the league, against Auxerre, and will be able to pass clean cards to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA disciplinary committee has sanctioned two matches for the team’s coach, José Mourinho, and different economic amounts for the players involved.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances such as this or similar is not a new practice, but rather frequent in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, of the unwritten rules, but followed, of this sport.
Part of the debate that arose in the reported case is due to the fact that it has been played by a team of the entity of Real Madrid (which in its anthem boasts of nobility and honor, and that in past times has fined its players for similar acts) and to the dramatization orchestrated, apparently, by Mourinho, who adds one more episode to its dilated technical history.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this type of behavior not expressly prohibited by the regulations contradicts the principles of sport, i.e. whether these actions are a violation of the law; in fact, they are actions that are respectful of the sports regulations, but seem to circumvent their meaning.
The point is to examine the type of damage they cause to the sporting spirit.
One of the goods that comprises the sports spirit is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that with these actions was not endangered, that is, there was no violent game.
Another of these assets that is alluded to with fair play is to prevent the team of the offending players from unfairly taking advantage of the opposing team, which also did not happen.
Now, the paradox of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that he did not settle for what we normally characterize as cheating or fraud of the law, because his violation of the rules was not done in secret to try to avoid the sanction, but precisely his action tried to be the most obvious in order to receive the punishment of the referee.
They waited and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage do the offenders gain in the intentional faults examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that the opponent is not placed in a disadvantageous situation or profit is obtained in the same game, because obviously the result of the action involves leaving the team itself with fewer players.
And it is also not a useful strategy for the next match, as the club will not be able to count on those players.
The advantage, obviously, is that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that may threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indeterminacy, because the team can be eliminated at the first exchange, and also with this performance the players fulfill a penalty game and move to the second cycle of cards, in which the suspension by accumulation of cards occurs with a less than in the first cycle.
So, from going through rounds, it’s not so clear that it’s an advantage.
In short, these actions do not go against the spirit of sports, of which it is part to make strategic decisions that favor to make the most of what the rules allow.
In the case before us, the players did not act to evade the application of the sanction (this would be a clear case of fraud of law), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without passing the punishment or fleeing from it.
Although the line between ingenuity and law fraud is blurred, this time I think it was a clear case of ingenuity.
The controversy, it seems to me, arises from two factors: because it was about two self-expulsions and because of the way in which the transmission of the directive to provoke them was carried out.
The damage caused to the principles of the sport by these actions is not so much ethical as aesthetic.
