Pakistan's nuclear program raises serious concerns in US
Islamabad produces atomic weapons at “a faster pace than any other country.”
WikiLeaks leaks confirm ties between the Taliban and Pakistan.
The content of the correspondence between the U.S. embassy in Pakistan and the U.S. State Department leaked by the WikiLeaks portal confirms the huge concerns that the Pakistani nuclear program causes in Washington.
Aside from the enlightening and juicy details they offer about the content of the conversations and thoughts of U.S. diplomatic representatives accredited in Islamabad, the documents reveal that cooperation between the two countries on nuclear security, rather than going up, “decreases,” and that the unstable Asian country produces nuclear weapons “at a faster rate than any other country.”
The peculiarity of Pakistan's nuclear program - that weapons are not assembled but remain stored by components to make it difficult to destroy in the event of an attack - is one of the main reasons for the unveiling in Washington.
The ambassador to Pakistan, Anne W. Patterson, listed it in a report ahead of the visit of then National Security Adviser James Jones: “The proximity of some nuclear facilities to territory under Taliban attack, the rumored dispersion of nuclear materials, and the vulnerability of the transport of atomic materials.”
The high number of people involved in nuclear arsenals and missile programs is contemplated, not only by the United States, but also by Russia, as a proliferator and a reason to keep watch.
"Pakistan has had to hire personnel with strict religious beliefs to protect nuclear facilities; given the fall in educational and cultural levels, extremist organizations have more opportunities to recruit people who work in nuclear or missile programs," Russian Foreign Ministry expert Yuri Korolev said at a meeting with his U.S. counterparts.
The latest in the documentation leaked by Julian Assange’s portal is the ever-increasing cooperation between the US and Pakistan on nuclear proliferation issues and Pakistan’s high rate of nuclear weapons production.
A statement from the embassy in May, which described the communication with Pakistan as "frustrating", said: "Transparency is often non-existent; offers of help remain unanswered or are discarded."
In another message, Peter Lavoy, a national intelligence official for South Asia, notes that “despite the economic catastrophe, Pakistan produces nuclear weapons at a faster rate than any other country in the world.”
Ambassador Patterson also calls on Washington, during a visit by the head of the army, General Ashfaq Kayani, to make “very clear” to the official that “the Pakistan Army must end the tacit support of terrorist groups.”
In the hunt for the head of WikiLeaks
Obama appoints a senior counterterrorism official to prevent further leaks.
Interpol issues a red alert in order to follow the movements and locate Assange wherever he is.
Everything related to WikiLeaks and its founder, Julian Assange, forms a complicated labyrinth where it is difficult to be sure of the facts.
Yesterday Interpol issued a “red alert” to “locate and follow Assange’s movements.”
However, this is not a traditional arrest warrant.
Also, it is not new, but dates from November 20.
And it has nothing to do with the latest leak of more than a quarter of a million U.S. diplomatic documents but with the allegations of sexual abuse that the Australian faces in Sweden.
Mark Stephens, a lawyer for WikiLeaks founder Mark Stephens, said: “The police know where and how to get in touch with Mr Assange.”
It was the 20th day when the international police force based in Lyon (France) issued the order at the request of Sweden, but did not reveal it until yesterday, after receiving authorization from the authorities of that country.
Interpol’s 188 countries have indications of identifying or locating Assange “with a view to his provisional arrest and extradition.”
Although Interpol cannot order the arrest of an individual affected by a red alert, many of the member countries, the organization has explained, do consider the so-called “notice” network free to proceed with an arrest – which must be committed by the national police force – especially if they have a bilateral extradition agreement, as is the case in Sweden and England, where Assange is believed to be.
The move has outraged Assange’s lawyers, who published a letter yesterday denouncing that the 39-year-old WikiLeaks founder has been willing to answer questions from Swedish authorities by video conference.
They also recall that Assange requested and obtained permission to leave Sweden from the prosecutor of his case, which they compare to the mythical Lavrentiy Pavlovich Beria, Stalin’s head of security.
“This looks like a hunt, not a legal persecution,” the letter said.
As the world searches for him – and from Australia his mother defends his son’s innocence – Assange remains in unknown but not silent whereabouts.
On Monday, he gave an indefinite interview to Time magazine’s director via Skype, a conversation in which he called for the resignation of U.S. Secretary of State Hillary Clinton.
“If it can be shown that he was responsible for ordering U.S. diplomats to spy on the UN in violation of international treaties that the U.S. has signed, he should resign,” he said.
His opinion was debunked yesterday by White House press secretary Robert Gibbs, who called the resignation request "ridiculous and absurd."
“I’m not entirely sure why we should care about a guy’s opinion with a website,” he told CNN.
Obama himself has tasked a senior counterterrorism official, Russell Travers, with preventing further leaks of documents.
President Barack Obama’s attempt to detract from Assange contrasts with views that politicians and conservative commentators proclaim these days.
Peter King, the congressman who will chair the National Security Committee in the lower house from January, has asked the State Department to study the possibility of including WikiLeaks in the list of terrorist organizations “to intervene and their funds and prosecute anyone of any contribution or assistance to them.”
Further on, Tom Flanagan, an adviser to Canadian President Stephen Harper, has had to retract after saying Assange should “be killed.”
“Obama should make it a target and use an unmanned plane or something.”
Who did not apologize was Mike Huckabee, Baptist minister, former Arkansas governor and possible presidential candidate.
"Anyone in the government who leaked the information is guilty of treason and anything other than execution would be too kind a punishment," he told Fox News.
