China keeps targets to reduce greenhouse gases
The representative of that country at the COP16 said that his country has made enormous efforts to reduce the carbon footprint and detailed that it supports its offer to reduce by 2020 between 40 and 45 percent its greenhouse gas emissions.
China keeps its offer to reduce its greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, Su Wei, the country’s representative at COP16, said.
In his first public appearance at the 16th Conference of the Parties to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (COP16), Su Wei said that his country has made enormous efforts to reduce its carbon footprint and to reconvert its industry.
In fact, he said, over the past four years his country has invested $245 million in efforts to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
However, he made it clear that China would not change its objectives, but would continue to work together with the international community on that issue.
He noted that China’s climate change strategy is divided into four headings: dialogue; capacity building; institution building and support for pilot programmes.
In all these areas, progress has been made, including the adoption last year of a new Energy Act, which sets out the proposed targets for reducing gas emissions, he explained.
On the other hand, he stressed that in China, federal authorities have been working in a coordinated way with state and local authorities, to achieve the goals of energy saving, energy efficient use and emission reduction.
In addition, it has abounded, is underway or has already completed several multi-year plans, both funded by the Chinese government and by governments of other countries.
For example, he said, the Energy Efficiency Programme, which was implemented over the past five years and received investments from the United Nations (UN), the government and private initiative.
A provincial climate change project is also underway, another for the change of incandescent focus to savers and one more mitigation and adaptation, he detailed.
At the same table, Martin Krol, the country’s government’s scientific adviser on climate change, said China’s efforts have been greater than generally thought.
For example, he explained, per capita greenhouse gas emissions in China are six tons per person, while in the United States it is 100 tons; China is responsible for 9 percent of the historical contribution to pollution.
It has also made unprecedented efforts in energy use, such as increasing energy efficiency by 20 percent over the past five years and plans to do so much more by 2020.
