EU changes rules for obtaining visas
Individuals must visit the Visa Applicant Service Centers prior to their interview in the Consular Section; the cost will be lower and the waiting time will be shorter.
As of January 10, 2011, the procedure for processing a visa at the U.S. Embassy and consulates will change.
With the new procedure, most applicants will need to go to the Visa Applicant Service Centers (ASC) before their interview in the Consular Section.
ASC staff will take the applicant’s biometric information, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for applicants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, it will no longer be necessary to make a payment to arrange the appointment, another payment to process the visa application and another for the courier service to deliver the document.
The applicant will only make a single payment that will cover all three services.
The current fee will remain unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for on-demand visa cases (including temporary worker visas) and $390 for merchant and investor visas.
People who wish to renew their visa will not have to go to an interview with the Consular Officer, but will only go to the nearest ASC where they will present their documents and take their fingerprints.
Because biometric information will be taken at the ASC, applicants who require a second appointment to be interviewed at the Consular Section will remain in the ASC for less time than in the past.
Also, those applying for visas at the Consulates in Ciudad Juarez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of $26.
For additional information on the new visa application procedure, visit the following page http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visa-FAQs.html
